{
    "esm": "0.4.0",
    "metadata": {
        "name": "BarometricFormula",
        "description": "Barometric formula for an isothermal atmosphere: p(z) = p_0 * exp(-z/H). Gives the pressure at altitude z from the sea-level pressure p_0 and the atmospheric scale height H. Migrated from AtmosphericDynamics.jl@816cc391 src/seinfeld_pandis_ch1.jl:201 (`BarometricFormula` @component). Implements Seinfeld & Pandis Ch 1 Eq. 1.5 — the integrated form of the hydrostatic equation for an isothermal atmosphere. Parameterized as observed-only: z, H, and p_0 are inputs (parameters in standalone form), pressure_ratio and p are the algebraic outputs.",
        "tags": [
            "atmospheric_dynamics",
            "seinfeld-pandis",
            "observed-only",
            "ch1"
        ],
        "created": "2026-05-17T00:00:00Z",
        "authors": [
            "AtmosphericDynamics.jl contributors",
            "EarthSciModels migration (esm-ogjk)"
        ],
        "references": [
            {
                "citation": "Seinfeld, J. H., & Pandis, S. N. (2006). Atmospheric Chemistry and Physics: From Air Pollution to Climate Change, 2nd ed. Wiley. Chapter 1, Section 1.2 (Atmospheric pressure and density), Eq. 1.5 (barometric formula for an isothermal atmosphere). ISBN 978-0-471-72018-8."
            }
        ]
    },
    "models": {
        "BarometricFormula": {
            "reference": {
                "notes": "source_ref: AtmosphericDynamics.jl@816cc391:src/seinfeld_pandis_ch1.jl:201\nUpstream `BarometricFormula` is an MTK `@component` with p_0 as a `@constant`, z as a `@parameter`, and H, p, pressure_ratio as `@variables`. The upstream docstring documents H as an input (the scale height is supplied externally). For standalone serialization (and to make the component well-posed in isolation), H and p_0 are declared as parameters here alongside z — matching the (S, observed-only) classification in docs/migration-tracker.md and the sibling sp_ch1 migrations (ideal_gas.esm, scale_height.esm). The two algebraic equations pressure_ratio = exp(-z/H) and p = p_0*pressure_ratio are unchanged from upstream. Constant value p_0 = 101325.0 Pa comes from the upstream module's `P_0` (Seinfeld & Pandis Appendix A).\n\nTolerance rationale (model-level rel=1e-6): observed-only algebraic system (no ODE integration); 1e-6 covers float64 roundoff in the exp(-z/H) and p_0*pressure_ratio expression chain across the altitude range (0-20 km) and scale-height range (7.4-8.4 km)."
            },
            "tolerance": {
                "rel": 1.0e-6
            },
            "variables": {
                "z": {
                    "type": "parameter",
                    "units": "m",
                    "default": 0.0,
                    "description": "Altitude above sea level (sea-level datum z = 0)"
                },
                "H": {
                    "type": "parameter",
                    "units": "m",
                    "default": 8000.0,
                    "description": "Atmospheric scale height (supplied as an input; typical tropospheric value ~8 km)"
                },
                "p_0": {
                    "type": "parameter",
                    "units": "Pa",
                    "default": 101325.0,
                    "description": "Standard sea-level pressure (Seinfeld & Pandis Appendix A)"
                },
                "pressure_ratio": {
                    "type": "state",
                    "units": "1",
                    "description": "Pressure ratio p/p_0 (dimensionless)"
                },
                "p": {
                    "type": "state",
                    "units": "Pa",
                    "description": "Pressure at altitude z"
                }
            },
            "equations": [
                {
                    "lhs": "pressure_ratio",
                    "rhs": {
                        "op": "exp",
                        "args": [
                            {
                                "op": "-",
                                "args": [
                                    {
                                        "op": "/",
                                        "args": ["z", "H"]
                                    }
                                ]
                            }
                        ]
                    }
                },
                {
                    "lhs": "p",
                    "rhs": {
                        "op": "*",
                        "args": ["p_0", "pressure_ratio"]
                    }
                }
            ],
            "tests": [
                {
                    "id": "sea_level",
                    "description": "Sea-level datum (z = 0). The barometric formula reduces to pressure_ratio = 1 and p = p_0; this is the boundary condition the formula is anchored to.",
                    "parameter_overrides": {
                        "z": 0.0,
                        "H": 8000.0
                    },
                    "time_span": { "start": 0.0, "end": 1.0 },
                    "assertions": [
                        { "variable": "pressure_ratio", "time": 0.0, "expected": 1.0 },
                        { "variable": "p", "time": 0.0, "expected": 101325.0 }
                    ]
                },
                {
                    "id": "one_scale_height",
                    "description": "At z = H the pressure falls by exactly a factor e: pressure_ratio = exp(-1) ~ 0.3679, p = p_0/e. This is the defining property of the scale height (Seinfeld & Pandis Eq. 1.5).",
                    "parameter_overrides": {
                        "z": 8000.0,
                        "H": 8000.0
                    },
                    "time_span": { "start": 0.0, "end": 1.0 },
                    "assertions": [
                        { "variable": "pressure_ratio", "time": 0.0, "expected": 0.36787944117144233 },
                        { "variable": "p", "time": 0.0, "expected": 37275.38437669639 }
                    ]
                },
                {
                    "id": "troposphere_10km",
                    "description": "Pressure at 10 km altitude with H = 8000 m. Seinfeld & Pandis Table 1.4 lists ~265 mbar near this altitude; the isothermal-H estimate p ~ 290 mbar is within the textbook's stated 2% tolerance.",
                    "parameter_overrides": {
                        "z": 10000.0,
                        "H": 8000.0
                    },
                    "time_span": { "start": 0.0, "end": 1.0 },
                    "assertions": [
                        { "variable": "pressure_ratio", "time": 0.0, "expected": 0.2865047968601901 },
                        { "variable": "p", "time": 0.0, "expected": 29030.098541858762 }
                    ]
                },
                {
                    "id": "stratosphere_20km",
                    "description": "Deep-decay case at 20 km altitude (z = 2.5 H): pressure_ratio = exp(-2.5) ~ 0.082. Exercises the small-pressure tail of the exponential.",
                    "parameter_overrides": {
                        "z": 20000.0,
                        "H": 8000.0
                    },
                    "time_span": { "start": 0.0, "end": 1.0 },
                    "assertions": [
                        { "variable": "pressure_ratio", "time": 0.0, "expected": 0.0820849986238988 },
                        { "variable": "p", "time": 0.0, "expected": 8317.262485566545 }
                    ]
                },
                {
                    "id": "larger_scale_height",
                    "description": "Scale-height dependence: at fixed z = 8000 m, a larger H = 8400 m (warm-atmosphere value from scale_height.esm) gives a slower decay than one_scale_height. Verifies the H input is wired into the exponent.",
                    "parameter_overrides": {
                        "z": 8000.0,
                        "H": 8400.0
                    },
                    "time_span": { "start": 0.0, "end": 1.0 },
                    "assertions": [
                        { "variable": "pressure_ratio", "time": 0.0, "expected": 0.38582130682912413 },
                        { "variable": "p", "time": 0.0, "expected": 39093.343914461 }
                    ]
                },
                {
                    "id": "cold_scale_height",
                    "description": "Scale-height dependence: at fixed z = 8000 m, a smaller H = 7400 m (cold mid-troposphere value from scale_height.esm) gives a faster decay than one_scale_height.",
                    "parameter_overrides": {
                        "z": 8000.0,
                        "H": 7400.0
                    },
                    "time_span": { "start": 0.0, "end": 1.0 },
                    "assertions": [
                        { "variable": "p", "time": 0.0, "expected": 34372.3372591107 }
                    ]
                },
                {
                    "id": "nonstandard_p0",
                    "description": "Non-default sea-level pressure (p_0 = 100000 Pa) at z = 5000 m, H = 8000 m. Verifies p scales linearly with p_0 while pressure_ratio stays independent of p_0.",
                    "parameter_overrides": {
                        "z": 5000.0,
                        "H": 8000.0,
                        "p_0": 100000.0
                    },
                    "time_span": { "start": 0.0, "end": 1.0 },
                    "assertions": [
                        { "variable": "pressure_ratio", "time": 0.0, "expected": 0.5352614285189903 },
                        { "variable": "p", "time": 0.0, "expected": 53526.14285189903 }
                    ]
                }
            ],
            "examples": [
                {
                    "id": "pressure_vs_altitude",
                    "description": "Atmospheric pressure as a function of altitude for an isothermal atmosphere with H = 8000 m and standard sea-level pressure. Reproduces the canonical exponential pressure-altitude curve of Seinfeld & Pandis Eq. 1.5 from the surface to 30 km.",
                    "initial_state": {
                        "type": "per_variable",
                        "values": {}
                    },
                    "parameters": {
                        "H": 8000.0
                    },
                    "time_span": { "start": 0.0, "end": 1.0 },
                    "parameter_sweep": {
                        "type": "cartesian",
                        "dimensions": [
                            {
                                "parameter": "z",
                                "range": { "start": 0.0, "stop": 30000.0, "count": 31, "scale": "linear" }
                            }
                        ]
                    },
                    "plots": [
                        {
                            "id": "p_vs_z",
                            "type": "line",
                            "description": "Pressure p as a function of altitude z at H = 8000 m (Eq. 1.5).",
                            "x": { "variable": "z", "label": "Altitude (m)" },
                            "y": { "variable": "p", "label": "Pressure (Pa)" }
                        }
                    ]
                },
                {
                    "id": "pressure_over_altitude_and_scale_height",
                    "description": "Two-dimensional sweep over altitude z (surface to 20 km) and scale height H (cold to warm atmosphere, 7-9 km). Surfaces the joint dependence of pressure on altitude and on the scale height that sets the decay rate.",
                    "initial_state": {
                        "type": "per_variable",
                        "values": {}
                    },
                    "parameters": {},
                    "time_span": { "start": 0.0, "end": 1.0 },
                    "parameter_sweep": {
                        "type": "cartesian",
                        "dimensions": [
                            {
                                "parameter": "z",
                                "range": { "start": 0.0, "stop": 20000.0, "count": 12, "scale": "linear" }
                            },
                            {
                                "parameter": "H",
                                "range": { "start": 7000.0, "stop": 9000.0, "count": 12, "scale": "linear" }
                            }
                        ]
                    },
                    "plots": [
                        {
                            "id": "p_heatmap",
                            "type": "heatmap",
                            "description": "Pressure p as a function of altitude z and scale height H.",
                            "x": { "variable": "z", "label": "Altitude (m)" },
                            "y": { "variable": "H", "label": "Scale height (m)" },
                            "value": { "variable": "p", "reduce": "final" }
                        }
                    ]
                }
            ]
        }
    }
}
